## Why This Is Asked
Illustrates mismatch between security controls and high-volume logging. Tests ability to design tamper-evident systems with concrete tech, key management, and incident response.

## Key Concepts
- Tamper-evident logging
- Signature schemes and KMS/HSM
- Immutable storage
- Key rotation and revocation
- Ingestion verification and alerting

## Code Example
```javascript
// Example signing function using Node.js crypto and AWS KMS
const crypto = require('crypto');
async function signLogEntry(keyId, payload) {
  const signer = crypto.createSign('SHA256');
  signer.update(payload);
  signer.end();
  // In real use, sign with KMS: return await kms.sign({KeyId: keyId, Message: signer.sign()...})
  return signer.sign(null, 'base64');
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you detect a stale signature after key rotation?
- What are the trade-offs of per-event signing vs per-batch signing?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests a practical, scalable OTA security approach for automotive platforms, focusing on hardware attestation, provenance, and rapid rollback under real-world constraints.

## Key Concepts

- Hardware root of trust (HSM/TPM), per-ECU attestation
- SBOM enforcement (CycloneDX)
- Reproducible builds and delta updates
- Per-device revocation and short-lived certs
- Incident response and rollback playbooks

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo: manifest verification against signature
const crypto = require('crypto');
const publicKey = fs.readFileSync('/trusted/keys/ecu.pub');
const manifest = fs.readFileSync('/update/manifest.json');
const signature = fs.readFileSync('/update/manifest.sig');
const ok = crypto.verify('SHA256', manifest, publicKey, signature);
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you handle revocation propagation during partial connectivity?
- How would you validate rollback safety under a corrupted delta?

## Why This Matters
WebSocket connections accept requests from any origin by default. Without origin checks, attackers can steal real-time data by tricking users into visiting malicious sites that initiate WebSocket connections to your service.

## The Patch Plan

### Step 1: Origin Whitelist Enforcement
Check the `Origin` header during the WebSocket upgrade handshake. Only allow domains you explicitly trust (e.g., `https://app.example.com`):

```javascript
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = ['https://app.example.com'];

function validateOrigin(origin) {
  return ALLOWED_ORIGINS.includes(origin);
}
```

### Step 2: Token Authentication Requirement
Require a valid auth token in the upgrade request. Validate the token before proceeding with the WebSocket upgrade. Reject the connection if the token is missing, invalid, or expired.

### Step 3: Bind Token to Connection
After validation, attach the token's user data (userId, permissions, scopes) to the WebSocket connection object. This allows tracking who is connected throughout the session.

### Step 4: Per-Connection Scopes
When sending messages, check the bound user data and only send data that the connected user is authorized to access. Implement channel-level or resource-level access control.

## Minimal Code Sketch

```javascript
const WebSocket = require('ws');
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = ['https://app.example.com'];

const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ noServer: true });

wss.on('connection', (ws, req) => {
  const user = req.user; // Set by auth middleware
  ws.userId = user.id;
  ws.scopes = user.scopes;

  // Only send data this user is authorized to see
  ws.send = (data) => {
    if (authorize(user, data)) {
      ws.send(JSON.stringify(data));
    }
  };
});

wss.on('upgrade', (request, socket, head) => {
  const origin = request.headers.origin;

  // Step 1: Origin check
  if (!ALLOWED_ORIGINS.includes(origin)) {
    socket.write('HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden\r\n\r\n');
    socket.destroy();
    return;
  }

  // Step 2: Token validation
  const token = request.headers['sec-websocket-protocol'] || getTokenFromUrl(request.url);
  const user = validateToken(token);
  if (!user) {
    socket.write('HTTP/1.1 401 Unauthorized\r\n\r\n');
    socket.destroy();
    return;
  }

  // Step 3: Proceed with upgrade
  request.user = user;
  wss.handleUpgrade(request, socket, head, (ws) => {
    wss.emit('connection', ws, request);
  });
});
```

## Test Plan

| Test Case | Expected Result |
|-----------|------------------|
| Request from allowed origin + valid token | Connection accepted |
| Request from disallowed origin | 403 Forbidden |
| Request with no token | 401 Unauthorized |
| Request with expired/invalid token | 401 Unauthorized |
| User A connects, User B sends message | User A should not receive User B's private data |

Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design secure multi-tenant serverless with real-world constraints: isolation, attestation, key management, deployment safety, and auditability.

Key Concepts

- Tenant isolation and sandboxing
- Hardware-backed signing (HSM) and per-tenant keys
- Runtime attestation and manifest/SBOM checks
- Ephemeral credentials and mTLS
- Canary deployments, rollback, tamper-evident logs
- Key rotation and incident response

Code Example

```javascript
// Example: verify signed package manifest before deployment
const crypto = require('crypto');
const manifest = loadManifest(tenantId);
const signatureBase64 = loadSignature(tenantId);
const publicKeyPem = loadPublicKey(tenantId);

const verifier = crypto.createVerify('SHA256');
verifier.update(manifest);
