- **Memory-Side Channels**: Attacks exploiting timing variations or access patterns in shared GPU memory
- **Data-Oblivious Programming**: Writing kernels whose behavior is independent of actual data values
- **Remote Attestation**: Verifying the integrity of the execution environment before trusting it with sensitive workloads
- **Constant-Time Kernels**: Ensuring execution time does not leak information through timing side channels
- **ORAM (Oblivious RAM)**: Protocols that obscure access patterns to prevent pattern-based attacks
- **Auditability**: Maintaining security logs while ensuring they do not become a leakage vector

## Code Example

```c
// Constant-time access pattern to prevent data-dependent indexing
static inline uint8_t ct_get(const uint8_t *a, size_t i, size_t n, uint8_t def) {
    uint8_t v = def;
    for (size_t j = 0; j < n; j++) {
        v |= a[j] * (1 - secure_cmp(i, j));
    }
    return v;
}

// Secure comparison using constant-time arithmetic
static inline uint8_t secure_cmp(size_t a, size_t b) {
    volatile size_t diff = a ^ b;
    return (diff | -diff) >> (sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 1);
}
```

This pattern ensures consistent memory access patterns regardless of the actual index being accessed, preventing timing-based information leakage.

